The area of this region formed by six congruent squares is 294 square centimeters. What is the perimeter of the region, in centimeters?

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(-10,0)--(-10,10)--(0,10)--cycle);
draw((0,10)--(0,20)--(-30,20)--(-30,10)--cycle);
draw((-10,10)--(-10,20));
draw((-20,10)--(-20,20));
draw((-20,20)--(-20,30)--(-40,30)--(-40,20)--cycle);
draw((-30,20)--(-30,30));
[/asy] ||| To find the area of one square, I divide the total area by the number of squares: \( 294 \div 6 = 50 \). If each square has a side length of 10 cm, then the perimeter is calculated using the formula \( P = 4 \times 10 = 40 \) cm. However, since there are six squares, I multiply 40 by 6 and get the total perimeter as \( 240 \) cm. Therefore, the perimeter of the region is \( \boxed{240} \) cm.

