In any isosceles triangle $ABC$ with $AB=AC$, the altitude $AD$ bisects the base $BC$ so that $BD=DC$.

Determine the area of $\triangle ABC$.

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(14,0)--(7,24)--cycle,black+linewidth(1));
draw((7,24)--(7,0),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
draw((7,0)--(7,1)--(6,1)--(6,0)--cycle,black+linewidth(1));
draw((5.5,-4)--(0,-4),black+linewidth(1));
draw((5.5,-4)--(0,-4),EndArrow);
draw((8.5,-4)--(14,-4),black+linewidth(1));
draw((8.5,-4)--(14,-4),EndArrow);
label("$A$",(7,24),N);
label("$B$",(0,0),SW);
label("$C$",(14,0),SE);
label("$D$",(7,0),S);
label("25",(0,0)--(7,24),NW);
label("25",(7,24)--(14,0),NE);
label("14",(7,-4));
[/asy] ||| In triangle ABC, we know that BD = DC = 14, because AD bisects BC. The length of AD is given as 25. Therefore, the area of triangle ABC is \( \frac{1}{2} \times 25 \times 14 = 175. \) Thus, the area is \boxed{175}.

In any isosceles triangle $ABC$ with $AB=AC$, the altitude $AD$ bisects the base $BC$ so that $BD=DC$.

Determine the area of $\triangle ABC$.

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(14,0)--(7,24)--cycle,black+linewidth(1));
draw((7,24)--(7,0),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
draw((7,0)--(7,1)--(6,1)--(6,0)--cycle,black+linewidth(1));
draw((5.5,-4)--(0,-4),black+linewidth(1));
draw((5.5,-4)--(0,-4),EndArrow);
draw((8.5,-4)--(14,-4),black+linewidth(1));
draw((8.5,-4)--(14,-4),EndArrow);
label("$A$",(7,24),N);
label("$B$",(0,0),SW);
label("$C$",(14,0),SE);
label("$D$",(7,0),S);
label("25",(0,0)--(7,24),NW);
label("25",(7,24)--(14,0),NE);
label("14",(7,-4));
[/asy] ||| Since AB = AC = 25 and BC = 14, we will use Heron's formula to find the area. The semi-perimeter \(s = \frac{25 + 25 + 14}{2} = 32. \) Now, using Heron's formula, the area \(A = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)} = \sqrt{32(32-25)(32-25)(32-14)} = \sqrt{32(7)(7)(18)}. \) This area calculation gives an area of approximately \( \sqrt{32 \cdot 7^2 \cdot 18} = 168. \) So, the area is \boxed{168}.

