Olga purchases a rectangular mirror (the shaded region) that fits exactly inside a frame. The outer perimeter of the frame measures 60 cm by 80 cm. The width of each side of the frame is 10 cm. What is the area of the mirror?

[asy]
unitsize(0.15inch);
defaultpen(black);
draw(((0,0)--(8,0)--(8,6)--(0,6)--cycle));
draw(((1,1)--(7,1)--(7,5)--(1,5)--cycle));
fill(((1,1)--(7,1)--(7,5)--(1,5)--cycle),gray);
draw(((0,-.7)--(2.3,-.7)));
draw(((5.7,-.7)--(8,-.7)));
draw(((0,-.5)--(0,-.9)));
draw(((8,-.5)--(8,-.9)));
label("80 cm",(4,0),S);
draw(((-1.8,0)--(-1.8,2.5)));
draw(((-1.8,3.5)--(-1.8,6)));
draw(((-2,0)--(-1.6,0)));
draw(((-2,6)--(-1.6,6)));
label("60 cm",(0,3),W);
draw(((7,6.7)--(8,6.7)));
draw(((7,6.5)--(7,6.9)));
draw(((8,6.5)--(8,6.9)));
label("10 cm",(7.5,6.7),N);
[/asy] ||| The outer perimeter of the frame is 60 cm by 80 cm, and since the width of the frame is 10 cm on each side, I will subtract 10 cm twice from each dimension. Thus, the mirror measures 50 cm by 70 cm. Calculating the area gives: 50 cm \times 70 cm = 3500 \ \text{cm}^2. Therefore, the area of the mirror is \boxed{3500 \ \text{cm}^2}.

