An equilateral triangle and a square are inscribed in a circle as shown. $ABC$ is isosceles. The triangle and square share a common vertex. What is the number of degrees in the measure of the angle indicated by the question mark?

[asy]

import markers; defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));

pair A,B,C,D,E,F,G;

draw(unitcircle);

A=(-1,0);
B=(0,-1);
C=(1,0);
D=(0,1);

draw(A--B--C--D--A);

E=(-0.9,-0.45);
F=(0.9,-0.45);

draw(D--E--F--D);

G=(-0.76,-0.23);

markangle(Label("?"),n=1,radius=10,D,G,A,marker(stickframe(n=0),true));

label("$A$",(-0.5,-0.34));
label("$B$",(0.5,-0.34));
label("$C$",B,S);

[/asy] ||| To find the angle at vertex $Z$, we start with angle $XYZ$. Since this is an angle of the square, we know that $\angle XYZ = 90^\circ$. The large angle at vertex $X$ can be divided into three angles: $90^\circ = \angle YXZ + 30^\circ + \angle YXZ = 2 \angle YXZ + 30^\circ$. Therefore, solving for $\angle YXZ$, we get $\angle YXZ = 30^\circ$. The mystery angle then is $\angle XZY = 180^\circ - 90^\circ - 30^\circ = \boxed{60^\circ}$.

