\end{align*}
Since there are no repeating digits, I concluded the 20th digit is the 0 in the non-repeating decimal, and so I believe the answer is  oxed{0}.

Two points are drawn on each side of a square with an area of 81 square units, dividing the side into 3 congruent parts.  Quarter-circle arcs connect the points on adjacent sides to create the figure shown.  What is the length of the boundary of the bolded figure?  Express your answer as a decimal to the nearest tenth. [asy]
size(80);
import graph;
draw((0,0)--(3,0)--(3,3)--(0,3)--cycle, linetype("2 4"));
draw(Arc((0,0),1,0,90),linewidth(.8));
draw(Arc((0,3),1,0,-90),linewidth(.8));
draw(Arc((3,0),1,90,180),linewidth(.8));
draw(Arc((3,3),1,180,270),linewidth(.8));
draw((1,0)--(2,0),linewidth(.8));draw((3,1)--(3,2),linewidth(.8));
draw((1,3)--(2,3),linewidth(.8));draw((0,1)--(0,2),linewidth(.8));
[/asy] ||| The square has an area of 81 square units, which means the side length is \( \sqrt{81} = 9 \) units. The length of the boundary consists of four straight segments of \( 9 \div 2 = 4.5 \) units each and four semicircular arcs. Since the four semicircles together form a full circle of radius \( 4.5 \div 2 = 2.25 \), the total arc length is approximately \( \pi \cdot 2.25 = 7.06858 \). The total length of the straight segments is \( 4.5 \cdot 4 = 18 \). Thus, the overall boundary length is \( 18 + 7.06858 = 25.06858 \), which rounds to \boxed{25.1}.

