In the diagram, what is the value of $y$?

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(18,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((18,0)--(18,-6),black+linewidth(1));
draw((0,0)--(4,6)--(18,-6),black+linewidth(1));
draw((18,0)--(18,-0.5)--(17.5,-0.5)--(17.5,0)--cycle,black+linewidth(1));
label("$80^{\circ}$",(4.5,5),S);
label("$60^{\circ}$",(1,0),NE);
label("$y^{\circ}$",(18.25,-5),NW);
[/asy] ||| To find the value of $y$, we look at triangle $ABC$. We know \( \angle ABC + \angle BAC + \angle BCA = 180^\circ \). Given that \( \angle ABC = 80^\circ \) and \( \angle BAC = 60^\circ \), we can substitute these values in. \[
 80^\circ + 60^\circ + \angle BCA = 180^\circ 
\]
This gives us:\[
\angle BCA = 180^\circ - 140^\circ = 40^\circ
\]
Now, we assume \( \angle CED\) is equal to \(y\), so \(\angle DCE = 40^\circ\) means that \(y + 40 = 70\). Therefore, \(y = 30^\circ\). So the final answer is \(\boxed{30}\).

