Points $A$, $B$, $C$ and $D$ are midpoints of the sides of the larger square.  If the larger square has area 60, what is the area of the smaller square? [asy]
pair a=(0,1),b=(1,0),c=(0,-1),d=(-1,0);
draw((-1,-1)--(-1,1)--(1,1)--(1,-1)--cycle);
draw(a--b--c--d--cycle);
label("$A$", a, N);
label("$B$", b, E);
label("$C$", c, S);
label("$D$", d, W);
[/asy] ||| To find the area of the smaller square, we first take the side length of the larger square. Since the area of the larger square is 60, we have \( \text{side length} = \sqrt{60} \). The midpoints create the smaller square, which also has a side length of \( \frac{\sqrt{60}}{2} \). Hence, the area of the smaller square is \( \left(\frac{\sqrt{60}}{2}\right)^2 = \frac{60}{4} = 15 \). So, the area of the smaller square is \boxed{15}.

