Two circles have the same center O. Point X is the midpoint of segment OP. What is the ratio of the area of the circle with radius OX to the area of the circle with radius OP? Express your answer as a common fraction.

[asy]
import graph;
draw(Circle((0,0),20));
draw(Circle((0,0),12));
dot((0,0));
dot((20,0));
dot((12,0));
draw((0,0)--(20,0));
label("$O$",(0,0),SE);
label("$P$",(20,0),E);
label("$X$",(12,0),SE);
[/asy] ||| If $X$ is the midpoint of segment $OP$, then the radius $OX$ is actually equal to the radius $OP$. Therefore, the ratio of the areas of the circles is $1:1$ which means it equals $ rac{1}{1}$. Thus, the answer is $\boxed{1}$.

