[/asy] ||| Let the leg length of the isosceles right triangle be $x$, so the hypotenuse of the triangle is $x\sqrt{2}$. The area of the square would then be $(x\sqrt{2})^2 = 2x^2$. The area of the triangle is again $\frac{x^2}{2}$. Therefore, the area of the pentagon is $2x^2 + \frac{x^2}{2} = \frac{5x^2}{2}$. This leads to the incorrect conclusion that the fraction of the pentagon occupied by the triangle is $\frac{2x^2/2}{5x^2/2} = \frac{2}{5} = \boxed{40\%}$.

Find $160\div \left(10+11\cdot 2\right)$. ||| To solve $160 \div \left(10 + 11 \cdot 2\right)$, I will first calculate the expression inside the parentheses. I will do the addition first and then the multiplication. So, 
\begin{align*} 
10 + 11 \cdot 2 &= 10 + 11 \times 2 \ 
&= 10 + 11 \ 
&= 21. 
\end{align*} 
Now substituting back, we get \begin{align*} 160 \div 21 &= 7.619. 
\end{align*} 
Thus, the answer is \boxed{7.619}.

Find $160\div \left(10+11\cdot 2\right)$. ||| To evaluate $160 \div \left(10 + 11 \cdot 2\right)$, I will calculate $11 \cdot 2$ first since multiplication is performed before addition. So,  
\begin{align*} 
11 \cdot 2 &= 22. 
\end{align*} 
Now I will add 10 to 22: 
\begin{align*} 
10 + 22 &= 32. 
\end{align*} 
Next, I will perform the division: 
\begin{align*} 160 \div 32 &= 8. 
\end{align*} 
Therefore, my final answer is \boxed{8}.
